<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th item, Chicago-datelined story on the commodities
trial, to CORRECT that two traders were convicted and a third
acquitted of commodity fraud, the least serious charges against
them.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge ordered a complete overhaul of
the financially ailing Manville trust fund created to compensate
tens of thousands of victims of asbestos-related disease nationwide.
   Using sharply critical language, U.S. District Judge Jack B.
Weinstein also supported but did not order on Monday a global
settlement of an estimated 130,000 claims filed by asbestos victims
dating to the 1940s.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the world's seven richest nations have
opened summit talks divided over aid to the Soviet Union but
pointed toward a compromise allowing each country to go its own way.
   Diplomatic sources also said Monday that six of the nations were
inclined to maintain trade restrictions against China, with only
Japan poised to end the commercial sanctions imposed after last
year's anti-democracy crackdown.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Standing apart from its summit partners, the Bush
administration renewed its opposition to any concrete guide for
reducing pollutants blamed for warming the earth's atmosphere.
   Shortly before the seven-nation summit formally opened, White
House chief of staff John Sununu reiterated American worries that
efforts to curtail polluting emissions sharply would hamper
economic growth.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans took out $3.9 billion more in
consumer credit than they paid off in May, or 10 times the amount
incurred only a month earlier, the government reports.
   The Federal Reserve said Monday that consumer credit increased
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 6.5 percent, up from the
previous month's 0.6 percent. Net new debt in April totaled $390
million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury convicted two traders on commodity
fraud charges in a partial verdict returned in the first trial
stemming from an FBI sting operation at the world's two largest
futures exchanges.
   A third trader was acquitted Monday on two commodity fraud
counts. The commodity fraud charges were among the least serious
against the traders.
   U.S. District Judge Ann C. Williams declared a mistrial on
scores of other charges, including a racketeering count against one
of the defendants. The jury deliberated 11 days before announcing
it could not reach a decision on the other charges.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five major U.S. banks have expressed a willingess
to become the lead lenders for a $4.38 billion employee acquisition
of United Airlines, the union-led buyout group says.
   The development advances the union group toward its goal of
securing financing for the buyout by an Aug. 9 deadline.
   But none of the banks has yet signed loan agreements, and they
are insisting that a portion of the financing come from non-banking
sources such as aircraft suppliers, a union group source said
Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contract talks between Eastern Airlines and
the Air Line Pilots Association have reached an impasse, triggering
a 30-day cooling-off period, the two sides say.
   The latest round of talks started in mid-May, several weeks
after a federal bankruptcy court in New York appointed Martin
Shugrue as a trustee to take control of Eastern from Frank Lorenzo.
Lorenzo is chairman of Eastern parent Continental Airlines Holdings
Inc., the former Texas Air Corp.
   The 30-day cooling off period begins today, the two sides said
Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French investor accused of insider trading
on Rorer Group Inc. securities has settled the charges with federal
officials, the Securities and Exchange Commission has announced.
   Without admitting or denying wrongdoing, Robert Rossi agreed to
pay nearly $1.45 million in alleged illegal profits plus interest.
   The settlement disclosed Monday was approved by a federal judge
in New York on July 3.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese developer, Yoshiaki Tsutsumi, again
topped a list of the world's richest people, but the annual tally
has one conspicuous deletion this year: Donald J. Trump.
   But despite the financial troubles of the New York developer,
the United States continues to contain the world's largest number
of billionaries _ 62 _ according to estimates released by Forbes
magazine.
   In addition, there are 37 U.S. families with fortunes over $1
billion, Forbes says in its July 23 issue, released Monday.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market crept ahead Monday. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials rose 9.16 to 2,914.11 on top of Friday's 25.74-point
gain.
   Bond prices lost ground on signs of unexpected economic strength.
   The dollar finished mixed in light domestic trading.
   Cotton futures prices fell sharply; energy futures rallied;
sugar plummeted; precious metals were lower; grains and soybeans
were mixed; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
